        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-600 border-b-2 border-blue-600 pb-3 mb-6">Day 2: Philosophical Abstraction</h1>
        <h2 class="text-2xl text-gray-700 mb-4">Opening (15 minutes)</h2>
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-4">Recap and Transition: Analysis vs. Abstraction</h3>
        <ul class="list-disc ml-8 space-y-2">
            <li><span class="font-bold">Day 1 Recap (Analysis):</span> We broke down complex ideas (like "Necessity") into their smallest parts to test them. This is <span class="font-bold">Deductive</span> logic.</li>
            <li><span class="font-bold">Day 2 Introduction:</span> How do we <em>form</em> the big ideas in the first place? We use <span class="font-bold">Abstraction</span>â€”the opposite process.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6">Definition: Abstraction is Filtering</h3>
        <div class="definition">
            <span class="font-bold">Abstraction</span> is the process of looking at many different, specific events or objects, and then <span class="font-bold">filtering out all the specific details</span> to focus only on the <span class="font-bold">one, universal idea</span> that connects them all.
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-4">Visual aid: Diagram illustrating Inductive Reasoning, moving from Specific Observations to General Principle.</p>
    </div>

