    <!-- Slide 4: Distinction: Deduction vs. Induction -->
    <div class="slide" data-slide="4">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-600 border-b-2 border-blue-600 pb-3 mb-6">The Core Difference: Analysis vs. Abstraction</h1>
        <p class="text-lg">This is the most important distinction between Day 1 (Analysis) and Day 2 (Abstraction):</p>
        <div class="example-box bg-red-50 border-red-400 p-5 rounded-lg shadow-md mt-6">
            <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-red-700">1. Analysis is Deductive (Top-Down)</h2>
            <ul class="list-disc ml-6 space-y-1">
                <li>Starts with a <span class="font-bold">Universal Concept</span> (e.g., Justice).</li>
                <li>Breaks it down to test its <span class="font-bold">Specific Parts</span>.</li>
                <li>Logic moves from the General Rule to a Specific Case.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="example-box bg-green-50 border-green-400 p-5 rounded-lg shadow-md mt-6">
            <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-green-700">2. Abstraction is Inductive (Bottom-Up)</h2>
            <ul class="list-disc ml-6 space-y-1">
                <li>Starts with many <span class="font-bold">Specific Observations</span> (facts/events).</li>
                <li>Builds them up to create a <span class="font-bold">Universal Concept</span>.</li>
                <li>Logic moves from Specific Cases to a General Rule.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Slide 5: Group Work Scenario A (Greater Good) -->
    <div class="slide" data-slide="5">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-600 border-b-2 border-blue-600 pb-3 mb-6">Group Work: Scenario A</h1>
